# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wavelet-transform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] In mathematics, the **continuous wavelet transform** (**CWT**) is a formal (i.e., non-numerical) tool that provides an overcomplete representation of a signal by letting the translation and scale parameter of the wavelets vary continuously.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] where $\psi (t)$ is a continuous function in both the time domain and the frequency domain called the mother wavelet and the overline represents operation of complex conjugate.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] The main purpose of the mother wavelet is to provide a source function to generate the daughter wavelets which are simply the translated and scaled versions of the mother wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] To recover the original signal $x(t)$ , the first inverse continuous wavelet transform can be exploited.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] is admissible constant, where hat means Fourier transform operator.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Traditionally, this constant is called wavelet admissible constant.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] To recover the original signal $x(t)$ , the second inverse continuous wavelet transform can be exploited.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Such defined wavelet can be called as an analyzing wavelet, because it admits to time-frequency analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] An analyzing wavelet is unnecessary to be admissible.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] The scale factor a either dilates or compresses a signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] When the scale factor is relatively low, the signal is more contracted which in turn results in a more detailed resulting graph.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] However, the drawback is that low scale factor does not last for the entire duration of the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] On the other hand, when the scale factor is high, the signal is stretched out which means that the resulting graph will be presented in less detail.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Nevertheless, it usually lasts the entire duration of the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] In definition, the continuous wavelet transform is a convolution of the input data sequence with a set of functions generated by the mother wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] The convolution can be computed by using a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Normally, the output $X_{w}(a,b)$ is a real valued function except when the mother wavelet is complex.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] A complex mother wavelet will convert the continuous wavelet transform to a complex valued function.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] The power spectrum of the continuous wavelet transform can be represented by ${\frac {1}{a}}\cdot |X_{w}(a,b)|^{2}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] One of the most popular applications of wavelet transform is image compression.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] The advantage of using wavelet-based coding in image compression is that it provides significant improvements in picture quality at higher compression ratios over conventional techniques.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Since wavelet transform has the ability to decompose complex information and patterns into elementary forms, it is commonly used in acoustics processing and pattern recognition, but it has been also proposed as an instantaneous frequency estimator.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Moreover, wavelet transforms can be applied to the following scientific research areas: edge and corner detection, partial differential equation solving, transient detection, filter design, electrocardiogram (ECG) analysis, texture analysis, business information analysis and gait analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Wavelet transforms can also be used in Electroencephalography (EEG) data analysis to identify epileptic spikes resulting from epilepsy.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Wavelet transform has been also successfully used for the interpretation of time series of landslides and land subsidence, and for calculating the changing periodicities of epidemics.
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] Continuous Wavelet Transform (CWT) is very efficient in determining the damping ratio of oscillating signals (e.g. identification of damping in dynamic systems).
[src:wavelet-transform/continuous-wavelet-transform] CWT is also very resistant to the noise in the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The **Daubechies wavelets**, based on the work of Ingrid Daubechies, are a family of orthogonal wavelets defining a discrete wavelet transform and characterized by a maximal number of vanishing moments for some given support.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] With each wavelet type of this class, there is a scaling function (called the *father wavelet*) which generates an orthogonal multiresolution analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] In general the Daubechies wavelets are chosen to have the highest number *A* of vanishing moments, (this does not imply the best smoothness) for given support width (number of coefficients) 2*A*.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] There are two naming schemes in use, D*N* using the length or number of taps, and db*A* referring to the number of vanishing moments.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] So D4 and db2 are the same wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Among the 2*A*−1 possible solutions of the algebraic equations for the moment and orthogonality conditions, the one is chosen whose scaling filter has extremal phase.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The wavelet transform is also easy to put into practice using the fast wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Daubechies wavelets are widely used in solving a broad range of problems, e.g. self-similarity properties of a signal or fractal problems, signal discontinuities, etc.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The Daubechies wavelets are not defined in terms of the resulting scaling and wavelet functions; in fact, they are not possible to write down in closed form.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The graphs below are generated using the cascade algorithm, a numeric technique consisting of inverse-transforming [1 0 0 0 0 ... ] an appropriate number of times.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Note that the spectra shown here are not the frequency response of the high and low pass filters, but rather the amplitudes of the continuous Fourier transforms of the scaling (blue) and wavelet (red) functions.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Daubechies orthogonal wavelets D2–D20 resp. db1–db10 are commonly used.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Each wavelet has a number of *zero moments* or *vanishing moments* equal to half the number of coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] For example, D2 has one vanishing moment, D4 has two, etc.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] A vanishing moment limits the wavelets ability to represent polynomial behaviour or information in a signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] For example, D2, with one vanishing moment, easily encodes polynomials of one coefficient, or constant signal components.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] D4 encodes polynomials with two coefficients, i.e. constant and linear signal components; and D6 encodes 3-polynomials, i.e. constant, linear and quadratic signal components.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] This ability to encode signals is nonetheless subject to the phenomenon of *scale leakage*, and the lack of shift-invariance, which arise from the discrete shifting operation (below) during application of the transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Sub-sequences which represent linear, quadratic (for example) signal components are treated differently by the transform depending on whether the points align with even- or odd-numbered locations in the sequence.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The lack of the important property of shift-invariance, has led to the development of several different versions of a shift-invariant (discrete) wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Both the scaling sequence (low-pass filter) and the wavelet sequence (band-pass filter) (see orthogonal wavelet for details of this construction) will here be normalized to have sum equal 2 and sum of squares equal 2.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] In some applications, they are normalised to have sum ${\sqrt {2}}$ , so that both sequences and all shifts of them by an even number of coefficients are orthonormal to each other.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Obviously, this has positive values on (0,2).
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] with *R* some polynomial with real coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] shall be nonnegative on the interval [0,2] translates into a set of linear restrictions on the coefficients of *R*.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The values of *P* on the interval [0,2] are bounded by some quantity $4^{A-r},$ maximizing *r* results in a linear program with infinitely many inequality conditions.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] for *p* one uses a technique called spectral factorization resp.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] that can be factored into two linear factors.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] One can assign either one of the two linear factors to *p*(*Z*), thus one obtains 2*N* possible solutions.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] For extremal phase one chooses the one that has all complex roots of *p*(*Z*) inside or on the unit circle and is thus real.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] For Daubechies wavelet transform, a pair of linear filters is used.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Each filter of the pair should be a quadrature mirror filter.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Solving the coefficient of the linear filter $c_{i}$ using the quadrature mirror filter property results in the following solution for the coefficient values for filter of order 4.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Below are the coefficients for the scaling functions for D2-20.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The wavelet coefficients are derived by reversing the order of the scaling function coefficients and then reversing the sign of every second one, (i.e., D4 wavelet $\approx$ {−0.1830127, −0.3169873, 1.1830127, −0.6830127}).
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Mathematically, this looks like $b_{k}=(-1)^{k}a_{N-1-k}$ where *k* is the coefficient index, *b* is a coefficient of the wavelet sequence and *a* a coefficient of the scaling sequence.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] *N* is the wavelet index, i.e., 2 for D2.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Parts of the construction are also used to derive the biorthogonal Cohen–Daubechies–Feauveau wavelets (CDFs).
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] While software such as Mathematica supports Daubechies wavelets directly a basic implementation is possible in MATLAB (in this case, Daubechies 4).
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] This implementation uses periodization to handle the problem of finite length signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] Other, more sophisticated methods are available, but often it is not necessary to use these as it only affects the very ends of the transformed signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] It is assumed that *S*, a column vector with an even number of elements, has been pre-defined as the signal to be analyzed.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] It was shown by Ali Akansu in 1990 that the binomial quadrature mirror filter bank (binomial QMF) is identical to the Daubechies wavelet filter, and its performance was ranked among known subspace solutions from a discrete-time signal processing perspective.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] It was an extension of the prior work on binomial coefficient and Hermite polynomials that led to the development of the Modified Hermite Transformation (MHT) in 1987.
[src:wavelet-transform/daubechies-wavelet] The magnitude square functions of Binomial-QMF filters are the unique maximally flat functions in a two-band perfect reconstruction QMF (PR-QMF) design formulation that is related to the wavelet regularity in the continuous domain.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In numerical analysis and functional analysis, a **discrete wavelet transform** (**DWT**) is any wavelet transform for which the wavelets are discretely sampled.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] As with other wavelet transforms, a key advantage it has over Fourier transforms is temporal resolution: it captures both frequency *and* location information (location in time).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The DWT of a signal x is calculated by passing it through a series of filters.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The signal is also decomposed simultaneously using a high-pass filter h .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The outputs give the detail coefficients (from the high-pass filter) and approximation coefficients (from the low-pass).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] It is important that the two filters are related to each other and they are known as a quadrature mirror filter.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] However, since half the frequencies of the signal have now been removed, half the samples can be discarded according to Nyquist's rule.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This decomposition has halved the time resolution since only half of each filter output characterises the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] However, each output has half the frequency band of the input, so the frequency resolution has been doubled.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] the above summation can be written more concisely.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] However computing a complete convolution $x*g$ with subsequent downsampling would waste computation time.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The Lifting scheme is an optimization where these two computations are interleaved.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This decomposition is repeated to further increase the frequency resolution and the approximation coefficients decomposed with high- and low-pass filters and then down-sampled.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This is represented as a binary tree with nodes representing a sub-space with a different time-frequency localisation.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] At each level in the above diagram the signal is decomposed into low and high frequencies.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Due to the decomposition process the input signal must be a multiple of $2^{n}$ where n is the number of levels.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The filterbank implementation of wavelets can be interpreted as computing the wavelet coefficients of a discrete set of child wavelets for a given mother wavelet $\psi (t)$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] where j is the scale parameter and k is the shift parameter, both of which are integers.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Recall that the wavelet coefficient $\gamma$ of a signal $x(t)$ is the projection of $x(t)$ onto a wavelet, and let $x(t)$ be a signal of length $2^{N}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Now fix j at a particular scale, so that $\gamma _{jk}$ is a function of k only.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In light of the above equation, $\gamma _{jk}$ can be viewed as a convolution of $x(t)$ with a dilated, reflected, and normalized version of the mother wavelet, $h(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {2^{j}}}}\psi \left({\frac {-t}{2^{j}}}\right)$ , sampled at the points $1,2^{j},2\cdot {2^{j}},...,2^{N}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] But this is precisely what the detail coefficients give at level j of the discrete wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Therefore, for an appropriate choice of $h[n]$ and $g[n]$ , the detail coefficients of the filter bank correspond exactly to a wavelet coefficient of a discrete set of child wavelets for a given mother wavelet $\psi (t)$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] As an example, consider the discrete Haar wavelet, whose mother wavelet is $\psi =[1,-1]$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Then the dilated, reflected, and normalized version of this wavelet is $h[n]={\frac {1}{\sqrt {2}}}[-1,1]$ , which is, indeed, the highpass decomposition filter for the discrete Haar wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The filterbank implementation of the Discrete Wavelet Transform takes only O(*N*) in certain cases, as compared to O(*N* log *N*) for the fast Fourier transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Note that if $g[n]$ and $h[n]$ are both a constant length (i.e. their length is independent of N), then $x*h$ and $x*g$ each take O(*N*) time.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The wavelet filterbank does each of these two O(*N*) convolutions, then splits the signal into two branches of size N/2.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] But it only recursively splits the upper branch convolved with $g[n]$ (as contrasted with the FFT, which recursively splits both the upper branch and the lower branch).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] which leads to an O(*N*) time for the entire operation, as can be shown by a geometric series expansion of the above relation.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] As an example, the discrete Haar wavelet transform is linear, since in that case $h[n]$ and $g[n]$ are constant length 2.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The locality of wavelets, coupled with the O(*N*) complexity, guarantees that the transform can be computed online (on a streaming basis).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This property is in sharp contrast to FFT, which requires access to the entire signal at once.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] It also applies to the multi-scale transform and also to the multi-dimensional transforms (e.g., 2-D DWT).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The first DWT was invented by Hungarian mathematician Alfréd Haar.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] For an input represented by a list of $2^{n}$ numbers, the Haar wavelet transform may be considered to pair up input values, storing the difference and passing the sum.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This process is repeated recursively, pairing up the sums to prove the next scale, which leads to $2^{n}-1$ differences and a final sum.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The most commonly used set of discrete wavelet transforms was formulated by the Belgian mathematician Ingrid Daubechies in 1988.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This formulation is based on the use of recurrence relations to generate progressively finer discrete samplings of an implicit mother wavelet function; each resolution is twice that of the previous scale.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In her seminal paper, Daubechies derives a family of wavelets, the first of which is the Haar wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Interest in this field has exploded since then, and many variations of Daubechies' original wavelets were developed.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The dual-tree complex wavelet transform ( $\mathbb {C}$ WT) is a relatively recent enhancement to the discrete wavelet transform (DWT), with important additional properties: It is nearly shift invariant and directionally selective in two and higher dimensions.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] It achieves this with a redundancy factor of only $2^{d}$ , substantially lower than the undecimated DWT.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The multidimensional (M-D) dual-tree $\mathbb {C}$ WT is nonseparable but is based on a computationally efficient, separable filter bank (FB).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Other forms of discrete wavelet transform include the Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 wavelet developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Tabatabai in 1988 (used in JPEG 2000 or JPEG XS), the Binomial QMF developed by Ali Naci Akansu in 1990, the set partitioning in hierarchical trees (SPIHT) algorithm developed by Amir Said with William A.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Pearlman in 1996, the non- or undecimated wavelet transform (where downsampling is omitted), and the Newland transform (where an orthonormal basis of wavelets is formed from appropriately constructed top-hat filters in frequency space).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Wavelet packet transforms are also related to the discrete wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Complex wavelet transform is another form.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Complete Java code for a 1-D and 2-D DWT using Haar, Daubechies, Coiflet, and Legendre wavelets is available from the open source project: JWave.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Furthermore, a fast lifting implementation of the discrete biorthogonal CDF 9/7 wavelet transform in C, used in the JPEG 2000 image compression standard can be found here (archived 5 March 2012).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The figure on the right shows an example of applying the above code to compute the Haar wavelet coefficients on a sound waveform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The Haar DWT illustrates the desirable properties of wavelets in general.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] First, it can be performed in $O(n)$ operations; second, it captures not only a notion of the frequency content of the input, by examining it at different scales, but also temporal content, i.e. the times at which these frequencies occur.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Combined, these two properties make the Fast wavelet transform (FWT) an alternative to the conventional fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Due to the rate-change operators in the filter bank, the discrete WT is not time-invariant but actually very sensitive to the alignment of the signal in time.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] To address the time-varying problem of wavelet transforms, Mallat and Zhong proposed a new algorithm for wavelet representation of a signal, which is invariant to time shifts.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] According to this algorithm, which is called a TI-DWT, only the scale parameter is sampled along the dyadic sequence 2^j (j∈Z) and the wavelet transform is calculated for each point in time.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The discrete wavelet transform has a huge number of applications in science, engineering, mathematics and computer science.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Most notably, it is used for signal coding, to represent a discrete signal in a more redundant form, often as a preconditioning for data compression.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Practical applications can also be found in signal processing of accelerations for gait analysis, image processing, in digital communications and many others.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] It is shown that discrete wavelet transform (discrete in scale and shift, and continuous in time) is successfully implemented as analog filter bank in biomedical signal processing for design of low-power pacemakers and also in ultra-wideband (UWB) wireless communications.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Wavelets are often used to denoise two dimensional signals, such as images.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The following example provides three steps to remove unwanted white Gaussian noise from the noisy image shown.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Matlab was used to import and filter the image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The first step is to choose a wavelet type, and a level N of decomposition.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In this case biorthogonal 3.5 wavelets were chosen with a level N of 10.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Biorthogonal wavelets are commonly used in image processing to detect and filter white Gaussian noise, due to their high contrast of neighboring pixel intensity values.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Using these wavelets a wavelet transformation is performed on the two dimensional image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Following the decomposition of the image file, the next step is to determine threshold values for each level from 1 to N.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Birgé-Massart strategy is a fairly common method for selecting these thresholds.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Using this process individual thresholds are made for N = 10 levels.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Applying these thresholds are the majority of the actual filtering of the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The final step is to reconstruct the image from the modified levels.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This is accomplished using an inverse wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The resulting image, with white Gaussian noise removed is shown below the original image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] When filtering any form of data it is important to quantify the signal-to-noise-ratio of the result.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In this case, the SNR of the noisy image in comparison to the original was 30.4958%, and the SNR of the denoised image is 32.5525%.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The resulting improvement of the wavelet filtering is a SNR gain of 2.0567%.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Choosing other wavelets, levels, and thresholding strategies can result in different types of filtering.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In this example, white Gaussian noise was chosen to be removed.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Although, with different thresholding, it could just as easily have been amplified.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] To illustrate the differences and similarities between the discrete wavelet transform with the discrete Fourier transform, consider the DWT and DFT of the following sequence: (1,0,0,0), a unit impulse.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Notably, the middle approximation (2-term) differs.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] On the other hand, the Fourier approximation correctly shows a peak, and all points are within $1/4$ of their correct value, though all points have error.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The wavelet approximation, by contrast, places a peak on the left half, but has no peak at the first point, and while it is exactly correct for half the values (reflecting location), it has an error of $1/2$ for the other values.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This illustrates the kinds of trade-offs between these transforms, and how in some respects the DWT provides preferable behavior, particularly for the modeling of transients.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Watermarking using DCT-DWT alters the wavelet coefficients of middle-frequency coefficient sets of 5-levels DWT transformed host image, followed by applying the DCT transforms on the selected coefficient sets.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Prasanalakshmi B proposed a method that uses the HL frequency sub-band in the middle-frequency coefficient sets LHx and HLx in a 5-level Discrete Wavelet Transform (DWT) transformed image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This algorithm chooses a coarser level of DWT in terms of imperceptibility and robustness to apply 4×4 block-based DCT on them.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Consequently, higher imperceptibility and robustness can be achieved.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Also, the pre-filtering operation is used before extraction of the watermark, sharpening, and Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG) filtering, which increases the difference between the information of the watermark and the hosted image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The basic idea of the DWT for a two-dimensional image is described as follows: An image is first decomposed into four parts of high, middle, and low-frequency subcomponents (i.e., LL1, HL1, LH1, HH1) by critically subsampling horizontal and vertical channels using subcomponent filters.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The subcomponents HL1, LH1, and HH1 represent the finest scale wavelet coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The subcomponent LL1 is decomposed and critically subsampled to obtain the following coarser-scaled wavelet components.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] This process is repeated several times, which is determined by the application at hand.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] High-frequency components are considered to embed the watermark since they contain edge information, and the human eye is less sensitive to edge changes.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] In watermarking algorithms, besides the watermark's invisibility, the primary concern is choosing the frequency components to embed the watermark to survive the possible attacks that the transmitted image may undergo.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Transform domain techniques have the advantage of unique properties of alternate domains to address spatial domain limitations and have additional features.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The Host image is made to undergo 5-level DWT watermarking.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Embedding the watermark in the middle-level frequency sub-bands LLx gives a high degree of imperceptibility and robustness.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Consequently, LLx coefficient sets in level five are chosen to increase the robustness of the watermark against common watermarking attacks, especially adding noise and blurring attacks, at little to no additional impact on image quality.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Then, the block base DCT is performed on these selected DWT coefficient sets and embeds pseudorandom sequences in middle frequencies.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] 2.The four non-overlapping multi-resolution coefficient sets LL1, HL1, LH1, and HH1 are obtained initially.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Decomposition is performed till 5-levels and the frequency subcomponents {HH1, HL1, LH1,{{HH2, HL2, LH2, {HH3, HL3, LH3, {HH4, HL4, LH4, {HH5, HL5, LH5, LL5}}}}}} are obtained by computing the fifth level DWT of the image I.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Divide the final four coefficient sets: HH5, HL5, LH5 and LL5 into 4 x 4 blocks.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] DCT is performed on each block in the chosen coefficient sets.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] These coefficient sets are chosen to inquire about the imperceptibility and robustness of algorithms equally.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Scramble the fingerprint image to gain the scrambled watermark WS (i, j).
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Re-formulate the scrambled watermark image into a vector of zeros and ones.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Two uncorrelated pseudorandom sequences are generated from the key obtained from the palm vein.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] The number of elements in the two pseudorandom sequences must equal the number of mid-band elements of the DCT-transformed DWT coefficient sets.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Embed the two pseudorandom sequences with a gain factor α in the DCT-transformed 4x4 blocks of the selected DWT coefficient sets of the host image.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Instead of embedding in all coefficients of the DCT block, it is applied only to the mid-band DCT coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] If X is denoted as the matrix of the mid-band coefficients of the DCT transformed block, then embedding is done with watermark bit 0, and X' is updated as X+∝*PN0,watermarkbit=0 and done with watermark bit 1 and X' is updated as X+∝*PN1.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] Inverse DCT (IDCT) is done on each block after its mid-band coefficients have been modified to embed the watermark bits.
[src:wavelet-transform/discrete-wavelet-transform] To produce the watermarked host image, Perform the inverse DWT (IDWT) on the DWT-transformed image, including the modified coefficient sets.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] In mathematics, the **Haar wavelet** is a sequence of rescaled "square-shaped" functions which together form a wavelet family or basis.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Wavelet analysis is similar to Fourier analysis in that it allows a target function over an interval to be represented in terms of an orthonormal basis.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar sequence is now recognised as the first known wavelet basis and is extensively used as a teaching example.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The **Haar sequence** was proposed in 1909 by Alfréd Haar.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Haar used these functions to give an example of an orthonormal system for the space of square-integrable functions on the unit interval [0, 1].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The study of wavelets, and even the term "wavelet", did not come until much later.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] As a special case of the Daubechies wavelet, the Haar wavelet is also known as **Db1**.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar wavelet is also the simplest possible wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The technical disadvantage of the Haar wavelet is that it is not continuous, and therefore not differentiable.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This property can, however, be an advantage for the analysis of signals with sudden transitions (discrete signals), such as monitoring of tool failure in machines.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This function is supported on the right-open interval *I**n*,*k* = [ *k*2−*n*, (*k*+1)2−*n*), *i.e.*, it vanishes outside that interval.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] where $\delta _{ij}$ represents the Kronecker delta.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It follows in this case that the product of these two Haar functions is a multiple of the first Haar function, hence the product has integral 0.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It is complete in *L*2( $\mathbb {R}$ ): *The Haar system on the line is an orthonormal basis in* *L*2( $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Any continuous real function on [0, 1] can be approximated uniformly on [0, 1] by linear combinations of the constant function **1**, $\psi (t),\psi (2t),\psi (4t),\dots ,\psi (2^{n}t),\dots$ and their shifted functions.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The dual function of ψ(*t*) is ψ(*t*) itself.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] In this section, the discussion is restricted to the unit interval [0, 1] and to the Haar functions that are supported on [0, 1].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] with the addition of the constant function **1** on [0, 1].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] In Hilbert space terms, this Haar system on [0, 1] is a complete orthonormal system, *i.e.*, an orthonormal basis, for the space *L*2([0, 1]) of square integrable functions on the unit interval.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar system on [0, 1] —with the constant function **1** as first element, followed with the Haar functions ordered according to the lexicographic ordering of couples (*n*, *k*)— is further a monotone Schauder basis for the space *L**p*([0, 1]) when 1 ≤ *p* < ∞.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This basis is unconditional when 1 < *p* < ∞.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This is an orthonormal system but it is not complete.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] In the language of probability theory, the Rademacher sequence is an instance of a sequence of independent Bernoulli random variables with mean 0.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Khintchine inequality expresses the fact that in all the spaces *L**p*([0, 1]), 1 ≤ *p* < ∞, the Rademacher sequence is equivalent to the unit vector basis in ℓ*2*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] In particular, the closed linear span of the Rademacher sequence in *L**p*([0, 1]), 1 ≤ *p* < ∞, is isomorphic to ℓ*2*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The **Faber–Schauder system** is the family of continuous functions on [0, 1] consisting of the constant function **1**, and of multiples of indefinite integrals of the functions in the Haar system on [0, 1], chosen to have norm 1 in the maximum norm.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This system begins with *s*0 = **1**, then *s*1(*t*) = *t* is the indefinite integral vanishing at 0 of the function **1**, first element of the Haar system on [0, 1].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] These functions *s**n*,*k* are continuous, piecewise linear, supported by the interval *I**n*,*k* that also supports ψ*n*,*k*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The function *s**n*,*k* is equal to 1 at the midpoint *x**n*,*k* of the interval *I**n*,*k*, linear on both halves of that interval.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It takes values between 0 and 1 everywhere.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Faber–Schauder system is a Schauder basis for the space *C*([0, 1]) of continuous functions on [0, 1].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] of the series expansion of *f* in the Faber–Schauder system is the continuous piecewise linear function that agrees with *f* at the 2*n* + 1 points *k*2−*n*, where 0 ≤ *k* ≤ 2*n*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] gives a way to compute the expansion of *f* step by step.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Since *f* is uniformly continuous, the sequence {*f**n*} converges uniformly to *f*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It follows that the Faber–Schauder series expansion of *f* converges in *C*([0, 1]), and the sum of this series is equal to *f*.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The **Franklin system** is obtained from the Faber–Schauder system by the Gram–Schmidt orthonormalization procedure.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Since the Franklin system has the same linear span as that of the Faber–Schauder system, this span is dense in *C*([0, 1]), hence in *L*2([0, 1]).
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Franklin system is therefore an orthonormal basis for *L*2([0, 1]), consisting of continuous piecewise linear functions.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Franklin proved in 1928 that this system is a Schauder basis for *C*([0, 1]).
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Franklin system is also an unconditional Schauder basis for the space *L**p*([0, 1]) when 1 < *p* < ∞.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Franklin system provides a Schauder basis in the disk algebra *A*(*D*).
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This was proved in 1974 by Bočkarev, after the existence of a basis for the disk algebra had remained open for more than forty years.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Bočkarev's construction of a Schauder basis in *A*(*D*) goes as follows: let *f* be a complex valued Lipschitz function on [0, π]; then *f* is the sum of a cosine series with absolutely summable coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Bočkarev's basis for *A*(*D*) is formed by the images under *T* of the functions in the Franklin system on [0, π].
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Bočkarev's equivalent description for the mapping *T* starts by extending *f* to an even Lipschitz function *g*1 on [−π, π], identified with a Lipschitz function on the unit circle **T**.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Next, let *g*2 be the conjugate function of *g*1, and define *T*(*f*) to be the function in *A*(*D*) whose value on the boundary **T** of *D* is equal to *g*1 + i*g*2.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] When dealing with 1-periodic continuous functions, or rather with continuous functions *f* on [0, 1] such that *f*(0) = *f*(1), one removes the function *s*1(*t*) = *t* from the Faber–Schauder system, in order to obtain the **periodic Faber–Schauder system**.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The **periodic Franklin system** is obtained by orthonormalization from the periodic Faber–-Schauder system.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] One can prove Bočkarev's result on *A*(*D*) by proving that the periodic Franklin system on [0, 2π] is a basis for a Banach space *A**r* isomorphic to *A*(*D*).
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The space *A**r* consists of complex continuous functions on the unit circle **T** whose conjugate function is also continuous.
