[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Note that, the above matrix is an un-normalized Haar matrix.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar matrix required by the Haar transform should be normalized.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] From the definition of the Haar matrix H , one can observe that, unlike the Fourier transform, H has only real elements (i.e., 1, -1 or 0) and is non-symmetric.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Take the 8-point Haar matrix $H_{8}$ as an example.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The first row of $H_{8}$ measures the average value, and the second row of $H_{8}$ measures a low frequency component of the input vector.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The next two rows are sensitive to the first and second half of the input vector respectively, which corresponds to moderate frequency components.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The remaining four rows are sensitive to the four section of the input vector, which corresponds to high frequency components.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The **Haar transform** is the simplest of the wavelet transforms.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] This transform cross-multiplies a function against the Haar wavelet with various shifts and stretches, like the Fourier transform cross-multiplies a function against a sine wave with two phases and many stretches.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar transform is one of the oldest transform functions, proposed in 1910 by the Hungarian mathematician Alfréd Haar.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It is found effective in applications such as signal and image compression in electrical and computer engineering as it provides a simple and computationally efficient approach for analysing the local aspects of a signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar transform is derived from the Haar matrix.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] An example of a 4×4 Haar transformation matrix is shown below.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar transform can be thought of as a sampling process in which rows of the transformation matrix act as samples of finer and finer resolution.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Compare with the Walsh transform, which is also 1/–1, but is non-localized.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] However, the length should be a power of 2, i.e. $N=2^{k},k\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] It can be used to analyse the localized feature of signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] Due to the orthogonal property of the Haar function, the frequency components of input signal can be analyzed.
[src:wavelet-transform/haar-wavelet] The Haar transform matrix is real and orthogonal.
