[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] A **multiresolution analysis** (**MRA**) or **multiscale approximation** (**MSA**) is the design method of most of the practically relevant discrete wavelet transforms (DWT) and the justification for the algorithm of the fast wavelet transform (FWT).
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] It was introduced in this context in 1988/89 by Stephane Mallat and Yves Meyer and has predecessors in the microlocal analysis in the theory of differential equations (the *ironing method*) and the pyramid methods of image processing as introduced in 1981/83 by Peter J.
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] that satisfies certain self-similarity relations in time-space and scale-frequency, as well as completeness and regularity relations.
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] In the case of one continuous (or at least with bounded variation) compactly supported scaling function with orthogonal shifts, one may make a number of deductions.
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] The proof of existence of this class of functions is due to Ingrid Daubechies.
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] one can show that the space $W_{0}\subset V_{-1}$ , which is defined as the (closed) linear hull of the mother wavelet's integer shifts, is the orthogonal complement to $V_{0}$ inside $V_{-1}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] Or put differently, $V_{-1}$ is the orthogonal sum (denoted by $\oplus$ ) of $W_{0}$ and $V_{0}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/multiresolution-analysis] is a countable complete orthonormal wavelet basis in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] In mathematics, a **wavelet series** is a representation of a square-integrable (real- or complex-valued) function by a certain orthonormal series generated by a wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This article provides a formal, mathematical definition of an **orthonormal wavelet** and of the **integral wavelet transform**.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] A function $\psi \,\in \,L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ is called an **orthonormal wavelet** if it can be used to define a Hilbert basis, that is, a complete orthonormal system for the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions on the real line.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The Hilbert basis is constructed as the family of functions $\{\psi _{jk}:\,j,\,k\,\in \,\mathbb {Z} \}$ by means of dyadic translations and dilations of $\psi \,$ , $\psi _{jk}(x)=2^{\frac {j}{2}}\psi \left(2^{j}x-k\right),$ for integers $j,\,k\,\in \,\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] with convergence of the series understood to be convergence in norm.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Such a representation of f is known as a **wavelet series**.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This implies that an orthonormal wavelet is self-dual.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Here, $a=2^{-j}$ is called the **binary dilation** or **dyadic dilation**, and $b=k2^{-j}$ is the **binary** or **dyadic position**.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The fundamental idea of wavelet transforms is that the transformation should allow only changes in time extension, but not shape, imposing a restriction on choosing suitable basis functions.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Changes in the time extension are expected to conform to the corresponding analysis frequency of the basis function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] where t represents time and $\omega$ angular frequency ( $\omega =2\pi f$ , where f is ordinary frequency).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The higher the required resolution in time, the lower the resolution in frequency has to be.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The larger the extension of the analysis windows is chosen, the larger is the value of $\Delta t$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] In other words, the basis function $\psi$ can be regarded as an impulse response of a system with which the function $x(t)$ has been filtered.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The transformed signal provides information about the time and the frequency.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Therefore, wavelet-transformation contains information similar to the short-time-Fourier-transformation, but with additional special properties of the wavelets, which show up at the resolution in time at higher analysis frequencies of the basis function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The difference in time resolution at ascending frequencies for the Fourier transform and the wavelet transform is shown below.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Note however, that the frequency resolution is decreasing for increasing frequencies while the temporal resolution increases.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This consequence of the Fourier uncertainty principle is not correctly displayed in the Figure.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This shows that wavelet transformation is good in time resolution of high frequencies, while for slowly varying functions, the frequency resolution is remarkable.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Another example: The analysis of three superposed sinusoidal signals $y(t)\;=\;\sin(2\pi f_{0}t)\;+\;\sin(4\pi f_{0}t)\;+\;\sin(8\pi f_{0}t)$ with STFT and wavelet-transformation.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This produces as many coefficients as there are pixels in the image (i.e., there is no compression yet since it is only a transform).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] These coefficients can then be compressed more easily because the information is statistically concentrated in just a few coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This principle is called transform coding.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] After that, the coefficients are quantized and the quantized values are entropy encoded and/or run length encoded.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] A few 1D and 2D applications of wavelet compression use a technique called "wavelet footprints".
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For most natural images, the spectrum density of lower frequency is higher.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] As a result, information of the low frequency signal (reference signal) is generally preserved, while the information in the detail signal is discarded.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Wavelet image compression system involves filters and decimation, so it can be described as a linear shift-variant system.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The transformation system contains two analysis filters (a low pass filter $h_{0}(n)$ and a high pass filter $h_{1}(n)$ ), a decimation process, an interpolation process, and two synthesis filters ( $g_{0}(n)$ and $g_{1}(n)$ ).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The compression and reconstruction system generally involves low frequency components, which is the analysis filters $h_{0}(n)$ for image compression and the synthesis filters $g_{0}(n)$ for reconstruction.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] To evaluate such system, we can input an impulse $\delta (n-n_{i})$ and observe its reconstruction $h(n-n_{i})$ ; The optimal wavelet are those who bring minimum shift variance and sidelobe to $h(n-n_{i})$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Even though wavelet with strict shift variance is not realistic, it is possible to select wavelet with only slight shift variance.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] By observing the impulse responses of the two filters, we can conclude that the second filter is less sensitive to the input location (i.e. it is less shift variant).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Another important issue for image compression and reconstruction is the system's oscillatory behavior, which might lead to severe undesired artifacts in the reconstructed image.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] To achieve this, the wavelet filters should have a large peak to sidelobe ratio.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] So far we have discussed about one-dimension transformation of the image compression system.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This issue can be extended to two dimension, while a more general term - shiftable multiscale transforms - is proposed.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] As mentioned earlier, impulse response can be used to evaluate the image compression/reconstruction system.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For the input sequence $x(n)=\delta (n-n_{i})$ , the reference signal $r_{1}(n)$ after one level of decomposition is $x(n)*h_{0}(n)$ goes through decimation by a factor of two, while $h_{0}(n)$ is a low pass filter.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Similarly, the next reference signal $r_{2}(n)$ is obtained by $r_{1}(n)*h_{0}(n)$ goes through decimation by a factor of two.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] After L levels of decomposition (and decimation), the analysis response is obtained by retaining one out of every $2^{L}$ samples: $h_{A}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})=f_{h0}^{(L)}(n-n_{i}/2^{L})$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] On the other hand, to reconstruct the signal x(n), we can consider a reference signal $r_{L}(n)=\delta (n-n_{j})$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] If the detail signals $d_{i}(n)$ are equal to zero for $1\leq i\leq L$ , then the reference signal at the previous stage ( $L-1$ stage) is $r_{L-1}(n)=g_{0}(n-2n_{j})$ , which is obtained by interpolating $r_{L}(n)$ and convoluting with $g_{0}(n)$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Similarly, the procedure is iterated to obtain the reference signal $r(n)$ at stage $L-2,L-3,....,1$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] After L iterations, the synthesis impulse response is calculated: $h_{s}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})=f_{g0}^{(L)}(n/2^{L}-n_{j})$ , which relates the reference signal $r_{L}(n)$ and the reconstructed signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Finally, the peak to first sidelobe ratio and the average second sidelobe of the overall impulse response $h_{AS}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})$ can be used to evaluate the wavelet image compression performance.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Using a wavelet transform, the wavelet compression methods are adequate for representing transients, such as percussion sounds in audio, or high-frequency components in two-dimensional images, for example an image of stars on a night sky.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This means that the transient elements of a data signal can be represented by a smaller amount of information than would be the case if some other transform, such as the more widespread discrete cosine transform, had been used.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] While wavelet transforms offer theoretical advantages, their practical limitations have effectively limited wavelet compression to analyzing localized changes and transient signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Despite decades of research, wavelet-based compression systems for common multimedia like audio and video do not consistently match the efficiency and perceptual quality of current Discrete Cosine Transform-based systems.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For one-dimensional data like audio or ECGs, wavelets excel at representing and compressing transient signals—sudden, isolated events such as a drum hit in music or the sharp peaks in a heart rhythm.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For example, the discrete wavelet transform has been successfully applied for the compression of electrocardiograph (ECG) signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] However, for smooth, periodic signals, which make up much of typical audio, harmonic analysis in the frequency domain with Fourier-related transforms achieve better compression and sound quality.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Compressing data that has both transient and periodic characteristics may be done with hybrid techniques that use wavelets along with traditional harmonic analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For example, the Vorbis audio codec primarily uses the modified discrete cosine transform to compress audio (which is generally smooth and periodic), however allows the addition of a hybrid wavelet filter bank for improved reproduction of transients.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For higher-dimensional data, wavelet compression faces significant challenges.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] In video, for instance, modern compression techniques such as intra coding and motion compensation (predicting parts of an image based on what's next to it spatially and temporally) and mixed and dynamic block sizes become incredibly complex with wavelets because of their overlapping nature.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] This complexity translates to more processing power and slower speed, making them less practical for widespread use.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Furthermore, while wavelets might score well on traditional measures such as PSNR, DCT blocks create a perception of sharpness that wavelets often lack, requiring higher bitrates to achieve similar subjective quality.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Wavelets have some slight benefits over Fourier transforms in reducing computations when examining specific frequencies.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] However, they are rarely more sensitive, and indeed, the common Morlet wavelet is mathematically identical to a short-time Fourier transform using a Gaussian window function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The exception is when searching for signals of a known, non-sinusoidal shape (e.g., heartbeats); in that case, using matched wavelets can outperform standard STFT/Morlet analyses.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] The wavelet transform can provide us with the frequency of the signals and the time associated to those frequencies, making it very convenient for its application in numerous fields.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For instance, signal processing of accelerations for gait analysis, for fault detection, for the analysis of seasonal displacements of landslides, for design of low power pacemakers and also in ultra-wideband (UWB) wireless communications.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] A convolution can be implemented as a multiplication in the frequency domain.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] With this the following approach of implementation results into: There are many different types of wavelet transforms for specific purposes.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] See also a full list of wavelet-related transforms but the common ones are listed below: Mexican hat wavelet, Haar Wavelet, Daubechies wavelet, triangular wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Fault detection in electrical power systems.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Locally adaptive statistical estimation of functions whose smoothness varies substantially over the domain, or more specifically, estimation of functions that are sparse in the wavelet domain.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] For processing temporal signals in real time, it is essential that the wavelet filters do not access signal values from the future as well as that minimal temporal latencies can be obtained.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Time-causal wavelets representations have been developed by Szu et al and Lindeberg, with the latter method also involving a memory-efficient time-recursive implementation.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet-transform] Synchro-squeezed transform can significantly enhance temporal and frequency resolution of time-frequency representation obtained using conventional wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A **wavelet** is a wave-like oscillation with an amplitude that begins at zero, increases or decreases, and then returns to zero one or more times.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelets are termed a "brief oscillation".
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A taxonomy of wavelets has been established, based on the number and direction of its pulses.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelets are imbued with specific properties that make them useful for signal processing.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For example, a wavelet could be created to have a frequency of middle C and a short duration of roughly one tenth of a second.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] If this wavelet were to be convolved with a signal created from the recording of a melody, then the resulting signal would be useful for determining when the middle C note appeared in the song.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Mathematically, a wavelet correlates with a signal if a portion of the signal is similar.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Correlation is at the core of many practical wavelet applications.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] As a mathematical tool, wavelets can be used to extract information from many kinds of data, including audio signals and images.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Sets of wavelets are needed to analyze data fully.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] "Complementary" wavelets decompose a signal without gaps or overlaps so that the decomposition process is mathematically reversible.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Thus, sets of complementary wavelets are useful in wavelet-based compression/decompression algorithms, where it is desirable to recover the original information with minimal loss.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In formal terms, this representation is a wavelet series representation of a square-integrable function with respect to either a complete, orthonormal set of basis functions, or an overcomplete set or frame of a vector space, for the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This is accomplished through coherent states.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In classical physics, the diffraction phenomenon is described by the Huygens–Fresnel principle that treats each point in a propagating wavefront as a collection of individual spherical wavelets.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The characteristic bending pattern is most pronounced when a wave from a coherent source (such as a laser) encounters a slit/aperture that is comparable in size to its wavelength.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This is due to the addition, or interference, of different points on the wavefront (or, equivalently, each wavelet) that travel by paths of different lengths to the registering surface.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Multiple, closely spaced openings (e.g., a diffraction grating), can result in a complex pattern of varying intensity.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The word *wavelet* has been used for decades in digital signal processing and exploration geophysics.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The equivalent French word *ondelette* meaning "small wave" was used by Jean Morlet and Alex Grossmann in the early 1980s.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet theory is applicable to several subjects.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] All wavelet transforms may be considered forms of time-frequency representation for continuous-time (analog) signals and so are related to harmonic analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Discrete wavelet transform (continuous in time) of a discrete-time (sampled) signal by using discrete-time filterbanks of dyadic (octave band) configuration is a wavelet approximation to that signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The coefficients of such a filter bank are called the shift and scaling coefficients in wavelets nomenclature.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] These filterbanks may contain either finite impulse response (FIR) or infinite impulse response (IIR) filters.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The wavelets forming a continuous wavelet transform (CWT) are subject to the uncertainty principle of Fourier analysis respective sampling theory: given a signal with some event in it, one cannot assign simultaneously an exact time and frequency response scale to that event.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The product of the uncertainties of time and frequency response scale has a lower bound.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Thus, in the scaleogram of a continuous wavelet transform of this signal, such an event marks an entire region in the time-scale plane, instead of just one point.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Also, discrete wavelet bases may be considered in the context of other forms of the uncertainty principle.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are broadly divided into three classes: continuous, discrete and multiresolution-based.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In continuous wavelet transforms, a given signal of finite energy is projected on a continuous family of frequency bands (or similar subspaces of the *Lp* function space *L*2(**R**) ).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For instance the signal may be represented on every frequency band of the form [*f*, 2*f*] for all positive frequencies *f* > 0.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Then, the original signal can be reconstructed by a suitable integration over all the resulting frequency components.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The frequency bands or subspaces (sub-bands) are scaled versions of a subspace at scale 1.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This subspace in turn is in most situations generated by the shifts of one generating function ψ in *L*2(**R**), the *mother wavelet*.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For the example of the scale one frequency band [1, 2] this function is $\psi (t)=2\,\operatorname {sinc} (2t)-\,\operatorname {sinc} (t)={\frac {\sin(2\pi t)-\sin(\pi t)}{\pi t}}$ with the (normalized) sinc function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The subspace of scale *a* or frequency band [1/*a*, 2/*a*] is generated by the functions (sometimes called *child wavelets*) $\psi _{a,b}(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {a}}}\psi \left({\frac {t-b}{a}}\right),$ where *a* is positive and defines the scale and *b* is any real number and defines the shift.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The pair (*a*, *b*) defines a point in the right halfplane **R**+ × **R**.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For the analysis of the signal *x*, one can assemble the wavelet coefficients into a scaleogram of the signal.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] It is computationally impossible to analyze a signal using all wavelet coefficients, so one may wonder if it is sufficient to pick a discrete subset of the upper halfplane to be able to reconstruct a signal from the corresponding wavelet coefficients.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] One such system is the affine system for some real parameters *a* > 1, *b* > 0.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The corresponding discrete subset of the halfplane consists of all the points (*am*, *nb am*) with *m*, *n* in **Z**.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In any discretised wavelet transform, there are only a finite number of wavelet coefficients for each bounded rectangular region in the upper halfplane.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Still, each coefficient requires the evaluation of an integral.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In special situations this numerical complexity can be avoided if the scaled and shifted wavelets form a multiresolution analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This means that there has to exist an auxiliary function, the *father wavelet* φ in *L*2(**R**), and that *a* is an integer.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A typical choice is *a* = 2 and *b* = 1.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The most famous pair of father and mother wavelets is the Daubechies 4-tap wavelet.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Note that not every orthonormal discrete wavelet basis can be associated to a multiresolution analysis; for example, the Journe wavelet admits no multiresolution analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In analogy to the sampling theorem one may conclude that the space *Vm* with sampling distance 2*m* more or less covers the frequency baseband from 0 to 1/2*m*-1.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] As orthogonal complement, *Wm* roughly covers the band [1/2*m*−1, 1/2*m*].
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Both pairs of identities form the basis for the algorithm of the fast wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For practical applications, and for efficiency reasons, one prefers continuously differentiable functions with compact support as mother (prototype) wavelet (functions).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Being in this space ensures that one can formulate the conditions of zero mean and square norm one: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\psi (t)\,dt=0$ is the condition for zero mean, and $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|\psi (t)|^{2}\,dt=1$ is the condition for square norm one.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For *ψ* to be a wavelet for the continuous wavelet transform (see there for exact statement), the mother wavelet must satisfy an admissibility criterion (loosely speaking, a kind of half-differentiability) in order to get a stably invertible transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For the discrete wavelet transform, one needs at least the condition that the wavelet series is a representation of the identity in the space *L*2(**R**).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Most constructions of discrete WT make use of the multiresolution analysis, which defines the wavelet by a scaling function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This scaling function itself is a solution to a functional equation.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For the continuous WT, the pair (*a*,*b*) varies over the full half-plane **R**+ × **R**; for the discrete WT this pair varies over a discrete subset of it, which is also called *affine group*.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] These functions are often incorrectly referred to as the basis functions of the (continuous) transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In fact, as in the continuous Fourier transform, there is no basis in the continuous wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Time-frequency interpretation uses a subtly different formulation (after Delprat).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The wavelet transform is often compared with the Fourier transform, in which signals are represented as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In fact, the Fourier transform can be viewed as a special case of the continuous wavelet transform with the choice of the mother wavelet $\psi (t)=e^{-2\pi it}$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The main difference in general is that wavelets are localized in both time and frequency whereas the standard Fourier transform is only localized in frequency.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is similar to the wavelet transform, in that it is also time and frequency localized, but there are issues with the frequency/time resolution trade-off.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Multiplication with a rectangular window in the time domain corresponds to convolution with a $\operatorname {sinc} (\Delta _{t}\omega )$ function in the frequency domain, resulting in spurious ringing artifacts for short/localized temporal windows.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] With the continuous-time Fourier transform, $\Delta _{t}\to \infty$ and this convolution is with a delta function in Fourier space, resulting in the true Fourier transform of the signal $x(t)$ .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The window function may be some other apodizing filter, such as a Gaussian.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The choice of windowing function will affect the approximation error relative to the true Fourier transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A given resolution cell's time-bandwidth product may not be exceeded with the STFT.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] All STFT basis elements maintain a uniform spectral and temporal support for all temporal shifts or offsets, thereby attaining an equal resolution in time for lower and higher frequencies.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The resolution is purely determined by the sampling width.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In contrast, the wavelet transform's multiresolutional properties enables large temporal supports for lower frequencies while maintaining short temporal widths for higher frequencies by the scaling properties of the wavelet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This property extends conventional time-frequency analysis into time-scale analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The discrete wavelet transform is less computationally complex, taking O(*N*) time as compared to O(*N* log *N*) for the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This computational advantage is not inherent to the transform, but reflects the choice of a logarithmic division of frequency, in contrast to the equally spaced frequency divisions of the FFT which uses the same basis functions as the discrete Fourier transform (DFT).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This complexity only applies when the filter size has no relation to the signal size.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A wavelet without compact support such as the Shannon wavelet would require O(*N*2).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] An orthogonal wavelet is entirely defined by the scaling filter – a low-pass finite impulse response (FIR) filter of length 2*N* and sum 1.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In biorthogonal wavelets, separate decomposition and reconstruction filters are defined.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For analysis with orthogonal wavelets the high pass filter is calculated as the quadrature mirror filter of the low pass, and reconstruction filters are the time reverse of the decomposition filters.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Daubechies and Symlet wavelets can be defined by the scaling filter.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelets are defined by the wavelet function ψ(*t*) (i.e. the mother wavelet) and scaling function φ(*t*) (also called father wavelet) in the time domain.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The wavelet function is in effect a band-pass filter and scaling that for each level halves its bandwidth.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This creates the problem that in order to cover the entire spectrum, an infinite number of levels would be required.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The scaling function filters the lowest level of the transform and ensures all the spectrum is covered.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For a wavelet with compact support, φ(*t*) can be considered finite in length and is equivalent to the scaling filter *g*.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The wavelet only has a time domain representation as the wavelet function ψ(*t*).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For instance, Mexican hat wavelets can be defined by a wavelet function.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] See a list of a few continuous wavelets.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The development of wavelets can be linked to several separate trains of thought, starting with Alfréd Haar's work in the early 20th century.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Later work by Dennis Gabor yielded Gabor atoms (1946), which are constructed similarly to wavelets, and applied to similar purposes.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The JPEG 2000 standard was developed from 1997 to 2000 by a Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) committee chaired by Touradj Ebrahimi (later the JPEG president).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] It uses the CDF 9/7 wavelet transform (developed by Ingrid Daubechies in 1992) for its lossy compression algorithm, and the Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 discrete-time filter bank (developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Tabatabai in 1988) for its lossless compression algorithm.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A wavelet is a mathematical function used to divide a given function or continuous-time signal into different scale components.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Usually one can assign a frequency range to each scale component.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Each scale component can then be studied with a resolution that matches its scale.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A wavelet transform is the representation of a function by wavelets.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The wavelets are scaled and translated copies (known as "daughter wavelets") of a finite-length or fast-decaying oscillating waveform (known as the "mother wavelet").
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet transforms have advantages over traditional Fourier transforms for representing functions that have discontinuities and sharp peaks, and for accurately deconstructing and reconstructing finite, non-periodic and/or non-stationary signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are classified into discrete wavelet transforms (DWTs) and continuous wavelet transforms (CWTs).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Note that both DWT and CWT are continuous-time (analog) transforms.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] They can be used to represent continuous-time (analog) signals.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] CWTs operate over every possible scale and translation whereas DWTs use a specific subset of scale and translation values or representation grid.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] There are a large number of wavelet transforms each suitable for different applications.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] There are a number of generalized transforms of which the wavelet transform is a special case.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For example, Yosef Joseph Segman introduced scale into the Heisenberg group, giving rise to a continuous transform space that is a function of time, scale, and frequency.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] The CWT is a two-dimensional slice through the resulting 3d time-scale-frequency volume.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Another example of a generalized transform is the chirplet transform in which the CWT is also a two dimensional slice through the chirplet transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] An important application area for generalized transforms involves systems in which high frequency resolution is crucial.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For example, darkfield electron optical transforms intermediate between direct and reciprocal space have been widely used in the harmonic analysis of atom clustering, i.e. in the study of crystals and crystal defects.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Fractional wavelet transform (FRWT) is a generalization of the classical wavelet transform in the fractional Fourier transform domains.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This transform is capable of providing the time- and fractional-domain information simultaneously and representing signals in the time-fractional-frequency plane.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Generally, an approximation to DWT is used for data compression if a signal is already sampled, and the CWT for signal analysis.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Thus, DWT approximation is commonly used in engineering and computer science, and the CWT in scientific research.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Like some other transforms, wavelet transforms can be used to transform data, then encode the transformed data, resulting in effective compression.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] For example, JPEG 2000 is an image compression standard that uses biorthogonal wavelets.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This means that although the frame is overcomplete, it is a *tight frame* (see types of frames of a vector space), and the same frame functions (except for conjugation in the case of complex wavelets) are used for both analysis and synthesis, i.e., in both the forward and inverse transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] A related use is for smoothing/denoising data based on wavelet coefficient thresholding, also called wavelet shrinkage.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] By adaptively thresholding the wavelet coefficients that correspond to undesired frequency components smoothing and/or denoising operations can be performed.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are also starting to be used for communication applications.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM is the basic modulation scheme used in HD-PLC (a power line communications technology developed by Panasonic), and in one of the optional modes included in the IEEE 1901 standard.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM can achieve deeper notches than traditional FFT OFDM, and wavelet OFDM does not require a guard interval (which usually represents significant overhead in FFT OFDM systems).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Often, signals can be represented well as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] However, consider a non-continuous signal with an abrupt discontinuity; this signal can still be represented as a sum of sinusoids, but requires an infinite number, which is an observation known as Gibbs phenomenon.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This, then, requires an infinite number of Fourier coefficients, which is not practical for many applications, such as compression.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Wavelets are more useful for describing these signals with discontinuities because of their time-localized behavior (both Fourier and wavelet transforms are frequency-localized, but wavelets have an additional time-localization property).
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Because of this, many types of signals in practice may be non-sparse in the Fourier domain, but very sparse in the wavelet domain.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This is particularly useful in signal reconstruction, especially in the recently popular field of compressed sensing.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] (Note that the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is also localized in time and frequency, but there are often problems with the frequency-time resolution trade-off.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] This motivates why wavelet transforms are now being adopted for a vast number of applications, often replacing the conventional Fourier transform.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Many areas of physics have seen this paradigm shift, including molecular dynamics, chaos theory, ab initio calculations, astrophysics, gravitational wave transient data analysis, density-matrix localisation, seismology, optics, turbulence and quantum mechanics.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] In computer vision and image processing, the notion of scale space representation and Gaussian derivative operators is regarded as a canonical multi-scale representation.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Suppose we measure a noisy signal $x=s+v$ , where s represents the signal and v represents the noise.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Let the wavelet transform of x be $y=W^{T}x=W^{T}s+W^{T}v=p+z$ , where $p=W^{T}s$ is the wavelet transform of the signal component and $z=W^{T}v$ is the wavelet transform of the noise component.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Since W is orthogonal, the estimation problem amounts to recovery of a signal in iid Gaussian noise.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] As p is sparse, one method is to apply a Gaussian mixture model for p .
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] By setting coefficients that fall below a shrinkage threshold to zero, once the inverse transform is applied, an expectedly small amount of signal is lost due to the sparsity assumption.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Typically, the above-threshold coefficients are not modified during this process.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Some algorithms for wavelet-based denoising may attenuate larger coefficients as well, based on a statistical estimate of the amount of noise expected to be removed by such an attenuation.
[src:wavelet-transform/wavelet] Agarwal et al. proposed wavelet based advanced linear and nonlinear methods to construct and investigate Climate as complex networks at different timescales.
